President Uhuru Kenyatta will on Tuesday lead the nation in marking 39 years since the death of his father, Kenya's first president Mzee Jomo Kenyatta. The President is expected to lay a wreath at 8am at the mausoleum in Parliament’s precincts as has been the tradition. Before this, Uhuru will inspect a guard of honour mounted by the military. From there, he and his family will attend a memorial service at St Stephen’s Anglican Church, Jogoo Road, from 9am. This is according to a programme sent to newsrooms by  State House spokesman Manoah Esipisu. Read: [VIDEO] Raila, Uhuru share podium at Mzee Jomo Kenyatta memorial The ceremony has been observed every year by sitting presidents since Mzee Kenyatta’s death in his sleep in Mombasa on August 22, 1978. Among family members expected to attend the events are Uhuru's mother Mama Ngina Kenyatta and First Lady Margaret Kenyatta. Outgoing speaker of the National Assembly Justin Muturi, Chief of the Kenya Defense Forces Samson Mwathethe and other dignitaries are also expected. Mzee Kenyatta and other pioneers struggled to liberate the country from British colonialists. He was among the Kapenguria six freedom fighters who included the late Ochieng' Oneko, Paul Ngei, Fred Kubai, Bildad Kaggia and Kung'u Karumba, who were arrested in October 1952. They were accused of managing and being members of the Mau Mau, an uprising against the British rulers.